#Fitting upgrades explaines:
Looked at the code — these are three parked refinements from a prior fitting refactor, not bugs or blockers. Here's what each means in plain terms, and my honest read on timing.

What they actually are
1. Templating FIT_CD_ABS / FIT_SF_ABS to <T>.
These two are the "auxiliary fit basis" faces DFT uses to dodge 4-centre integrals (FIT_CD_ABS = density fit in the Coulomb metric; FIT_SF_ABS = scalar-function fit in the overlap metric). They're currently double-only classes. The "<dcmplx> vision" is to make them FIT_..._ABS<T> so the plane-wave (complex) path could share the same fitting abstraction instead of having its own. Parked because nothing needs complex fitting today — the PW path uses FourierFunctionFitter directly. Purely forward-looking generalization.

2. FourierFunctionFitter "delete-and-inline."
FourierFunctionFitter is the plane-wave fitter. In G-space with an orthonormal {G} basis, "fitting" is trivial (the coefficients are the field's Fourier components — no least-squares needed). The prior agent noted you could delete the little class and inline that trivial logic at the one call site. They kept the named class (conservative); the "aggressive alternative" is the inline. Pure code-tidiness — a keep-a-small-class-vs-inline judgment call, nothing depends on it.

3. XC energy ∫ε_xc·ρ through the fitter.
The XC energy is E_xc = ∫ ε_xc(ρ) ρ. Today exchange uses the virial shortcut E_x = ¾⟨ρ|v_x⟩ (exact for LDA exchange), and correlation goes through a dedicated FittedEpsXc fit. The vision is to route the whole thing uniformly through the fitter — but that needs the fitter to accept a grid-evaluated ε_xc as its fit input, which it doesn't cleanly do yet. This one has real future value — the ¾ virial shortcut breaks for GGA, so it becomes necessary when you add gradient functionals.

My recommendation: new session, and mostly "not yet"
None are urgent or blocking — they're "small follow-ups," and the session's already been a long one. More usefully, each has a natural trigger, and doing them before the trigger is speculative:

Item	Value now	Do it when…
1. Template fit faces	Low (no consumer)	You genuinely want PW and molecular DFT to share one fitting path — which is squarely part of your PP/PW-harmonization goal, so it may fall out of that work naturally
2. Delete-and-inline FourierFunctionFitter	Cosmetic	Never, unless it annoys you — or fold it into item 1
3. XC energy through the fitter	Medium	You tackle GGA (the virial shortcut fails there) — do it with the GGA work, not as an isolated cleanup
So: I'd leave all three on the TODO rather than spend this session on them. Item 1 is worth keeping in mind as you scope the PP-harmonization work (it's the same "unify real/complex" theme), and item 3 pairs naturally with GGA when you get there.

If you'd like, I can rewrite that TODO block with these triggers noted (so future-you/the next agent knows when each becomes worth doing) — but I wouldn't implement any of them right now.


